snippet.textDisplay: I buy Sunset tomatoes too sometimes, so not a perfecto hunzo here, BUT DON'T say these things have flavor. Sure, Winter/Spring greenhouse tomatoes are cool things to have, but ALL of these are F1 seeds which basically are designed for shelf-life and appearance at the expense of nutrients and flavor (and small-scale farms) . F1 tomatoes have the appearance of tomatoes but have none of the rest. These varieties have 30 to 70% less calcium, polyphenols, vitamin C, lycopene, or magnesium than in-season soil-grown "farmer's market"/heirloom tomatoes. I enjoy Brad's content like the next average YouTube consumer, but it seems like everyone is slowly drinking the kool-aid. I mean, congrats on the sponsorships, that's well deserved! But sad that more and more, Bon Appétit's basically advocating for things that are so wrong with our food system and food habits.
snippet.textOriginal: I buy Sunset tomatoes too sometimes, so not a perfecto hunzo here, BUT DON'T say these things have flavor. Sure, Winter/Spring greenhouse tomatoes are cool things to have, but ALL of these are F1 seeds which basically are designed for shelf-life and appearance at the expense of nutrients and flavor (and small-scale farms) . F1 tomatoes have the appearance of tomatoes but have none of the rest. These varieties have 30 to 70% less calcium, polyphenols, vitamin C, lycopene, or magnesium than in-season soil-grown "farmer's market"/heirloom tomatoes. I enjoy Brad's content like the next average YouTube consumer, but it seems like everyone is slowly drinking the kool-aid. I mean, congrats on the sponsorships, that's well deserved! But sad that more and more, Bon Appétit's basically advocating for things that are so wrong with our food system and food habits.
